            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Michael Sharma\u2019s story is one of quiet conviction, shaped more by love and loss than by ambition. Raised in a placid Ohio suburb, he felt an early pull towards the kinetic energy and progressive ideals of the West Coast. He landed at UC Berkeley in the early 90s, studying Public Policy with a fervent belief that well-designed systems could genuinely improve lives. It was there he met Anjali, a vibrant environmental science major, and fell deeply in love. In a move that puzzled his Midwestern family, he adopted her surname, Sharma, upon their marriage\u2014a testament to his devotion and their shared vision of building a new life on their own terms.\n\nThey settled in San Francisco, and Michael began his career with the city, taking an entry-level position at the Public Utilities Commission. For fifteen years, his life was a comfortable rhythm of work, love, and community. He and Anjali were a unit, hosting potlucks in their Inner Sunset apartment and spending weekends hiking in Marin. His steady ascent at the PUC paralleled their deepening partnership.\n\nThe turning point was swift and brutal. Anjali\u2019s cancer diagnosis at 42 felt like a betrayal by the universe. Her death two years later hollowed him out, leaving his steady life feeling fragile and anchorless. For a time, Michael merely existed. But gradually, he poured his grief into his work. Managing water infrastructure projects was no longer just a job; it became a tangible way to honor Anjali\u2019s environmentalist spirit\u2014a form of stewardship for the city they had both loved.\n\nNow, at 50, Michael\u2019s life is defined by a settled routine. His 3.8-mile commute on the N-Judah is a time for reading or simply watching the city wake up. His apartment near Golden Gate Park is a quiet sanctuary filled with photos of Anjali. His social life is a small, tight circle of old friends who understand his history. His hope is not for a grand new chapter, but for a graceful continuation of this one: to mentor the next generation at the PUC, to see his long-term projects ensure the city\u2019s resilience, and to find contentment in the enduring legacy of a life built, and rebuilt, in San Francisco."
