            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the steam rising from their coffee mugs at a cafe near Berkeley, just before graduation. When he said he wanted to take her name, \"Sharma,\" Anjali\u2019s eyes widened, then filled with a quiet understanding. It wasn't a grand gesture, but a foundational one. In that moment, he wasn't just joining her; they were consciously creating a new lineage together. It cemented his belief that their life would be built entirely on their own terms, a partnership of equals from the very start.\n\n2.\nHe recalls a specific Saturday in their mid-thirties, hiking the Dipsea Trail. Anjali, breathless and laughing, had pointed down at the fog blanketing the Pacific. She spoke about the water cycle not as a scientist, but as a poet, calling it the planet\u2019s circulatory system. He felt a profound, simple contentment, the warmth of the sun on his back matched by the warmth of her hand in his. That moment became his definition of happiness: uncomplicated, sun-drenched, and shared with her.\n\n3.\nOne afternoon during her illness, she was too weak to leave their apartment. A winter storm was rolling in, and they stood at the window together, watching rain streak the glass. \"All that runoff,\" she'd whispered, leaning her head on his shoulder, \"You make sure it gets where it needs to go, okay, Michael?\" The comment, so casually delivered, reframed his entire career. His job was no longer about pipes and policy; it was a sacred promise he was making to her.\n\n4.\nIt was almost a year after she was gone, standing on a misty reservoir overlook in the Peninsula. He was there for an inspection, but he suddenly saw it not as infrastructure, but as a monument. He could feel the weight of every drop of water, the sheer life-giving force of it, and understood it as a tangible piece of her environmentalist soul. His grief didn't vanish, but it shifted, finding a purpose. He wasn't just maintaining a system; he was tending her legacy.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on his morning N-Judah commute, the train paused at the tunnel\u2019s west portal. The sun broke through the fog, illuminating the top of a cypress tree in Golden Gate Park with an almost holy light. He didn\u2019t feel the sharp pang of loss, but a quiet, enduring connection. He thought, *She would have loved this light*. The memory was a gentle companion, not a ghost. It was in that small moment he realized he had found a kind of peace."
